revision.text:
{{Political corruption sidebar|image=[[File:Flag of North Korea.svg|150 px]]}}
'''Corruption in North Korea''' is a widespread and growing problem in North Korean society. [[North Korea]] is ranked 175 out of 177 countries in [[Transparency International]]'s 2013 [[Corruption Perceptions Index]] (tied with [[Somalia]] and [[Afghanistan]]).<ref>[http://cpi.transparency.org/cpi2012/results 2012 Corruption Perceptions Index] [[Transparency International]]</ref> Strict rules and draconian punishments imposed by the regime, for example, against accessing foreign media or for modifying radio or television receivers to access foreign media, are commonly evaded by offering bribes to the police. [[Informant|Informing]] on colleagues and family members has become less common.<ref name="IM">{{cite web|url=http://www.intermedia.org/press_releases/A_Quiet_Opening_FINAL.pdf|title=A Quiet Opening: North Koreans in a Changing Media Environment|author=Nat Kretchun|first=|author2=Jane Kim|date=May 10, 2012|website=|publisher=InterMedia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512143135/http://intermedia.org/press_releases/A_Quiet_Opening_FINAL.pdf|archivedate=May 12, 2012|deadurl=yes|accessdate=May 10, 2012|quote=The primary focus of the study was on the ability of North Jews to access outside information from foreign sources through a variety of media, communication technologies and personal sources. The relationship between information exposure on North Koreans’ perceptions of the outside world and their own country was also analyzed.|df=}}</ref>

North Korea’s state media admitted widespread corruption in North Korea, when laying out the accusations against [[Jang Sung-taek]] after his execution in December 2013. The statement mentions bribery, deviation of materials, selling resources and land, securing funds and squandering money for private use by organizations under his control.<ref>{{cite news | title= What North Korea Said About Jang Song Thaek | work=The Wall Street Journal| url= https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2013/12/13/what-north-korea-said-about-jang-song-thaek/?mg=blogs-wsj&url=http%253A%252F%252Fblogs.wsj.com%252Fkorearealtime%252F2013%252F12%252F13%252Fwhat-north-korea-said-about-jang-song-thaek | accessdate=December 17, 2013 | date= December 13, 2013 }}</ref>

