{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}} A '''gentleman's farm''' is a property that is owned by a '''gentleman farmer''' who has a farm as part of his estate and who farms mainly for pleasure rather than for profit or sustenance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Definition - "Gentleman Farmer"|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/gentleman-farmer|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2016 |accessdate=25 June 2016|quote=A country gentleman who has a farm as part of his estate.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Definition - Gentleman farmer|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/gentleman%20farmer|publisher=Merriam-Webster, An Encyclopædia Britannica Company|accessdate=25 June 2016|quote=A man who farms mainly for pleasure rather than for profit}}</ref> His acreage may produce any number of types of grains, poultry or other livestock. The estate can vary from under ten to hundreds or even thousands of acres. The gentleman farmer can employ labourers and farm managers. The chief source of income for the gentleman farmer was derived not from any income that the landed property may generate. He invariably had his own [[private income]], worked as a professional, owned a large business elsewhere, or some combination of the three.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Claudius Loudon|first1=John|title=An encyclopædia of agriculture ... Fourth edition, etc - Book I Agricultural Artists (Page 1123)|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=CqtgAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1123&lpg=PA1123&dq=gentlemen+farmers+acreage++professions&source=bl&ots=xs0Lxsn-bu&sig=z2rle1f0KswSu3brD5zcNuFbHjY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfqbS198LNAhUGkZQKHUCrCcoQ6AEIITAB#v=onepage&q=gentlemen%20farmers%20acreage%20%20professions&f=false|publisher=Longman, Orme, Brown, Green, &Longmans|year= 1839|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kames|first1=Lord Henry Home |title=The Gentleman Farmer: Being an Attempt to Improve Agriculture by Subjecting it to the Test of Rational Principles|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=DbICAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA67&lpg=PA67&dq=gentlemen+farmers+lord+acreage+sheep&source=bl&ots=_ootr5jvYb&sig=AnCSmU3brkqywzPat-evtySaO4A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjvKXY88LNAhWKkpQKHc9PCeoQ6AEIKjAE#v=onepage&q=gentlemen%20farmers%20lord%20acreage%20sheep&f=false|publisher=W. Creech, |year=1776|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Quinn|first1=Tom|title=Life on the Old Farm (Chapter - A Farming Dynasty)|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=4Tv8WOn_zCcC&pg=PT136&lpg=PT136&dq=gentleman+farmers+private+income&source=bl&ots=DtSkbGXpK6&sig=m0nEbFoegcJxP_rsEOPo6wo0Eik&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJz46xgMPNAhWFVZQKHUPxCYcQ6AEIODAE#v=onepage&q=gentleman%20farmers%20private%20income&f=false|publisher=David & Charles|date= 1 April 2012|accessdate=25 June 2016|quote=My father was a gentleman farmer in the sense that he had a private income... he didn't need to worry too much if the farm itself didn't make any money.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://encarta.msn.com/dictionary_1861694762/gentleman_farmer.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090920011717/http://encarta.msn.com/dictionary_1861694762/gentleman_farmer.html |title=Gentleman farmer|publisher= Encarta|accessdate= 19 July 2009| archivedate= 20 September 2009}}</ref>
Some notable gentleman farmers include [[James Roosevelt I]], the father of [[President Franklin Delano Roosevelt]], [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] who retired to a farm near [[Gettysburg, Pennsylvania]] after leaving the [[White House]], [[George Washington]], who farmed at [[Mount Vernon]], [[Winthrop Rockefeller]] son of [[John D. Rockefeller, Jr.]] who moved to Arkansas in 1953 and established Winrock Farms atop [[Petit Jean Mountain]], [[Frederick Hinde Zimmerman]],<ref>{{cite news |ref=harv|last=Unsigned|title = Fred Zimmerman Obituary | date =22 September 1924| work = Daily Republican Register }}</ref> [[Frank C. Rathje]], and William Locke Allison, known for [[Allison Woods]], which was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1995.<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a|dateform=dmy}}</ref>
